meaning_mnemonic: This L-shaped radical is the <radical>lion</radical> radical, because "L" is for "Lion." It also looks like a lion's mouth being opened really, really wide. Imagine a lion opening its mouth to yawn. It looks like this radical!

This is a <radical>knife</radical>. See the sharp edge on the left and the tapered tip on top? And there's a little handle at the bottom for the... well, the handle. Be careful you don't cut yourself on this knife!
There's a <radical>ladle</radical> scooping up two drops of liquid. See the handle and the scoop part of the ladle? Imagine ladling some water into your mouth. Mmm.

First of all, there's a cross making up the middle, which automatically makes this a religion-based radical. That cross is the frame of someone's body and the things coming off of it are wings. This is an <radical>angel</radical>.
This radical looks like the fire from the burner of a stove. That's because this is the <radical>boil</radical> radical. You need to boil a bunch of water over some flames.

This radical looks like a <radical>yakuza</radical>. See him facing left, with that threatening jawline and big pompadour hairstyle? Maybe imagine a couple scars on his face too. You know, real yakuza-like.

You could also remember this because it’s the evening radical under the ground radical, and people who do stuff underground in the evening (and night) are definitely yakuza.
There's a head with a little bit of hair on the top. There's also one big eye in the middle. Only one creature has a head like this, and that creature is the <radical>cyclops</radical>.

This is like one of those <radical>jet</radical>s that have the little nose-wings going on too. Imagine you're looking at the jet from the top down, this is what it would look like. It's also why this is the jet radical.

This is a tree with a drooping slide shape on top. What causes the top of plants to sag? The <radical>grain</radical>s. Imagine seeing how the heads of wheat or rice droop when they're ready for harvest. It will look like this radical. Look at all that ripe grain!

This might remind you of 米, which has three stalks sprouting upward. You can tell the difference because the top of this one is slanted from the weight of the ripe grain.
This is a very fluffy <radical>sheep</radical>. See the two horns poking up and all its wool poking out to the side? It's so fluffy that you can hardly see its tiny little legs. What a cute sheep!

You see a little drop of something on your plate. Oh no… it's <radical>BLOOD</radical>!!! Yep, you're bleeding. Now you have to wash that plate again — just as soon as the bleeding stops. Don't worry, your platelets should stop the bleeding soon. Haha, get it? PLATE-lets? Like blood platelets? Japanese blood jokes.
When a stick figure has hair that drags on the ground and gets kicked all the time, you know that hair's gotta be <radical>long</radical>. Why is it so looooong?!
You put on your hat and go outside to kick something white. It's a big white goose and you killed it with your kick. That's because you're going to cook and <radical>eat</radical> it. Yum!

This radical is just like the katakana character "ma" (マ). So let's keep things simple and make the radical <radical>mama</radical>. It even looks like a mama leaning over and gently tapping her baby to help them fall asleep.

Someone has a toe in their mouth. They are a fortune teller telling your <radical>fortune</radical>. But for her to do it, she has to take one of your toes and taste it. This better be a good fortune for you to let someone put your foot in their mouth.

This is the radical for <radical>neck</radical>. Look, you can see all the vertebrae stacked up, and the little ligaments that connect it to the base of the skull! That's why this is the radical for neck.

This is the <radical>tongue</radical> radical. See that sturdy slide holding a thousand people above a mouth? An open mouth can't support that much weight, but a strong tongue can — it's the muscle of the mouth, after all.

Alternatively, you can think of this as something sticking out of a mouth with thousands of tiny taste buds on it. It's your tongue!

There's a lid on a lion. And you're stuck under the lid with the lion, which means you will surely meet your <radical>death</radical>. Or if you don't want to die, think of the poor lion. If you leave a lion under a lid for too long, death will come for it too. Either way, somebody's gonna die today.
Behind that tree the sun is rising in the <radical>east</radical>. The sun always rises in the east, so if you head that way, past the tree, you'll be going east too.

This radical is the same as the kanji. It means <radical>city</radical>.

In case you don't remember the kanji's meaning mnemonic, here's a refresher:

You see a manhole <radical>lid</radical> and a <radical>towel</radical>, both with the name of a <kanji>city</kanji> on them. Decorative manhole lids and souvenir towels — two things cities love to slap their names on, especially in Japan.

Under this roof is a pig with her little ones. Your pig, because it's your <radical>house</radical>! You keep your piggies inside where it's nice and warm. They're all members of your family, so they deserve to live in your house too.

A <radical>leader</radical> with a <radical>spoon</radical> is a powerful thing. Even something as ordinary as a spoon can create great <kanji>change</kanji> in the world when given to the right person.
reading_mnemonic: Then, this hero of yours takes their spoon and says some magic words into it, <kanji>changing</kanji> it into a <reading>car</reading> (か).

meaning_mnemonic:
A <radical>dirt</radical> <radical>alligator</radical> lives in the <kanji>earth</kanji>, not the water. They can swim through the earth itself! Which is pretty scary.

You can think of this word as <kanji>ground</kanji> too, because that's kind of what earth is made of.
reading_mnemonic: The only way to keep this dirt alligator from dragging you under the <kanji>earth</kanji> and eating you is to feed it <reading>chee</reading>se (ち). That way it won't lead you to a horrific death under the earth by dragging you under and spinning you around until you eat dirt (literally).

meaning_mnemonic: As you dig under the <radical>ground</radical> you discover a <radical>head</radical> resting near a <radical>mountain</radical>, which are <kanji>both</kanji> strange things to find beneath the earth.
reading_mnemonic: But, you dig too deep and water flows into where you are. Your only hope is a <reading>row</reading> (りょう) boat floating off in the distance.

meaning_mnemonic: The <radical>hat</radical> crowns the <radical>king</radical>, because <kanji>all</kanji> kings must have one.
reading_mnemonic: But, as you're going through <kanji>all</kanji> the kings, it turns out not all of them have hats after all. The last one you come to is hatless. He's the king of <reading>Zen</reading> (ぜん). He has simple clothes and a shaved head, unlike all the other fancy kings standing around nearby.

meaning_mnemonic: A <radical>drop</radical> hits your <radical>mustache</radical>. Where did it come from? "Ah, it came from <kanji>yonder</kanji>," you say, <kanji>facing</kanji> that way.
reading_mnemonic: Who shot this drop at you from <kanji>yonder</kanji>? You look over yonder, and see a figure. It is <reading>こう</reading>いち.

meaning_mnemonic: With a <radical>roof</radical> over her head, a <radical>woman</radical> can <kanji>relax</kanji>. She doesn't have to worry about rain or snow or finding a place to sleep. The roof also happened to be super <kanji>cheap</kanji>, so she can even relax about her finances.
reading_mnemonic: As she <kanji>relax</kanji>es, she pulls out the <kanji>cheap</kanji>est, most relaxing food in the world: <reading>an</reading>chovies (あん).

meaning_mnemonic: Think about Japan. Japan is a country made up of islands. They're basically three <radical>drop</radical> <radical>drop</radical> <radical>drop</radical>s in the large <radical>river</radical> that is the Pacific Ocean. These are Japan's <kanji>states</kanji> or <kanji>province</kanji>s.
reading_mnemonic: Each <kanji>state</kanji> has its own <reading>shoe</reading> (しゅう) to represent it. The bottom of each shoe is the shape of the state, so when you step it leaves a state-shaped imprint in the ground.

meaning_mnemonic: There are <radical>mouth</radical>s, <radical>twenty</radical> of them, singing beautiful <kanji>music</kanji> together. The music seems to <kanji>bend</kanji> toward you through the air.
reading_mnemonic: The twenty mouths make so much <kanji>music</kanji> that they literally <reading>cloak you</reading> (きょく) with it. They cloak you with the music.

meaning_mnemonic: A <radical>narwhal</radical> and a <radical>moon</radical> is all you <kanji>have</kanji>. Imagine one of each under your arms.
reading_mnemonic: Everything you <kanji>have</kanji> (except the narwhal and the moon) were taken from you by a roving gang of <reading>you</reading>ths (ゆう).

meaning_mnemonic: If the <radical>yakuza</radical> hands you a <radical>spoon</radical>, <kanji>death</kanji> is coming for you. It's the death spoon, a sign that the yakuza is coming to cause your death.
reading_mnemonic: <kanji>Death</kanji> comes in the form of a <reading>shee</reading>p (し). The death sheep works for the yakuza, and kills anyone who has their spoon.

meaning_mnemonic: The <radical>sheep</radical> radical and the <kanji>sheep</kanji> kanji are the same in looks as well in meaning.
reading_mnemonic: To remember よう, we use the word "Yogurt." The <kanji>sheep</kanji> are after you. There are too many of them, and they're chasing you down, stalking you... because you stole their sheep's milk <reading>yo</reading>gurt (よう). Now you're running and crying and trying to eat the yogurt before the sheep catch up and stomp you down with their hooves.

meaning_mnemonic: The <radical>blood</radical> radical and <kanji>blood</kanji> are the same in looks as well as in meaning.
reading_mnemonic:
To remember the reading けつ, we use the word "ketsup." The perfect mix of ketchup and catsup!

The radical is technically <radical>blood</radical>, but you know that radical is just a drop (of blood) on a plate. So, you ask yourself... Is that really blood on the plate? Could it be? You decide to take a gamble and lick it off. When you taste it, it's definitely not blood. No, it's <reading>ketsup</reading> (けつ).

meaning_mnemonic: The <radical>mouth</radical> of the <radical>king</radical> extends all the way around him (like in this kanji). Where his mouth reaches, that is his <kanji>country</kanji>, give or take a few <radical>drop</radical>s.
reading_mnemonic: Turns out the king of this <kanji>country</kanji> loves drinking <reading>Coke</reading> (こく). Every morning that big mouth of his swallows a whole 2-liter bottle of Coke for breakfast.

meaning_mnemonic: Who's that <radical>woman</radical> pretending to be a <radical>jet</radical>? That's my <kanji>younger sister</kanji>. *Sigh*
reading_mnemonic: Your <kanji>younger sister</kanji> is giving some <reading>mi</reading>ce (まい) a ride on her back like a jet.

meaning_mnemonic: The only <radical>woman</radical> in this <radical>city</radical> is your <kanji>older sister</kanji>. She's the only woman surrounded by a bunch of men, but she's following her dreams in the big city.
reading_mnemonic: Your <kanji>older sister</kanji> may have moved to the city, but she kept her pet <reading>shee</reading>p (し) with her. Now the only woman in the city is your older sister, and the only sheep is her pet.

meaning_mnemonic: A long time ago, someone put up a <radical>canopy</radical> over their <radical>fortune</radical> telling booth and created the first <kanji>shop</kanji>. This <kanji>store</kanji> was fortune-based, but since then lots of different stores have popped up!
reading_mnemonic: This <kanji>shop</kanji> quickly turned into <reading>ten</reading> (てん) shops! It was a good idea, after all, so all of the other people selling goods and services decided to copy it and create their own shops. The next day there were ten more.

meaning_mnemonic: This is the same as the radical for <radical>east</radical>, so it means <kanji>east</kanji> too.
reading_mnemonic: You see a man walk straight toward the sun rising in the <kanji>east</kanji>. It's so bright he can't see anything, so he trips and <reading>he gash</reading>es (ひがし) his knee on a rock. Yikes… But he gets back up, determined to head east, and, oh no, he gashes his other knee! OK, he should probably give up on going east.

meaning_mnemonic: You <radical>stop</radical> at a <radical>small</radical> <radical>slide</radical>. What were you doing before you stopped here? You were <kanji>walk</kanji>ing.
reading_mnemonic: So, you're <kanji>walk</kanji>ing around, minding your own business, when suddenly something flips up and whacks you in the face. You stepped on the head of a <reading>hoe</reading> (ほ) and it caused it to swing up from the ground and hit you.

meaning_mnemonic: You take an <radical>arrow</radical> to the <radical>mouth</radical> because you <kanji>know</kanji> too much. You know some very sensitive information, and someone's sent a bow-slinging enforcer to pin your big blabbermouth shut with arrows.
reading_mnemonic: One of the things you <kanji>know</kanji> too much about is the <reading>shee</reading>p (し) plan for world domination! Yes, you know that sheep are in fact plotting to overthrow humanity and take over the world.

meaning_mnemonic:
The <radical>long</radical> radical and the <kanji>long</kanji> kanji are the same! 

This kanji also means <kanji>leader</kanji>, because the longer a person is, the better a leader they'll be. Or maybe it was... the longer they've been somewhere? Whatever, longness = leaderness, you know?
reading_mnemonic: You see a very <kanji>long</kanji> person. It's Mrs. <reading>Chou</reading> (ちょう), who has made herself long, like her street. "I made myself long so I can watch more of the street, my domain. I'm the <kanji>leader</kanji> of these streets. Watch yourself not-long person," says Mrs. Chou.

meaning_mnemonic:
There are some <radical>horns</radical> on the <radical>ground</radical> and a <radical>moon</radical> <radical>knife</radical> in <kanji>front</kanji> of you. When you try to move, they always rotate around with you, staying right in front. You can't escape these objects, for some reason.

This kanji means <kanji>before</kanji> too. Something that's in front of you is before you, after all.
reading_mnemonic: You're going crazy with these things in <kanji>front</kanji> of you all the time. You finally seek the help of a <reading>Zen</reading> (ぜん) master, who tells you that meditation will save you from this curse. You try it out, and sure enough, the objects are gone! It worked!

meaning_mnemonic: You put a <radical>roof</radical> over the <radical>ground</radical> to make your own <radical>private</radical> patch of <radical>dirt</radical>. This is your <kanji>room</kanji>! That's really all a room is, you know? A covered, private place where you can have some time to yourself.
reading_mnemonic: The only problem with your <kanji>room</kanji> is that you can't always be alone. Because of your dad's <reading>shih tzu</reading> (しつ). The shih tzu likes to come into your room and pee everywhere. Ruining your privacy completely.

meaning_mnemonic: If you <radical>loiter</radical> around to <radical>poop</radical> in <radical>winter</radical> you never know what could be happening <kanji>behind</kanji> you. <kanji>After</kanji> you're done you could turn <kanji>back</kanji> to see something really crazy that you missed because you took so long to poop in the cold.
reading_mnemonic: You finally look <kanji>behind</kanji> you and see <reading>Go</reading>dzilla (ご) and a giant <reading>こう</reading>いち having a violent battle <kanji>back</kanji> there!

meaning_mnemonic: In a <radical>rice paddy</radical> you find a <radical>heart</radical> and it makes you <kanji>think</kanji>. You think a lot of <kanji>thought</kanji>s like, "Whose heart is this? Why is it in a rice paddy? Why am I thinking out loud?"
reading_mnemonic: As you are <kanji>think</kanji>ing these <kanji>thought</kanji>s, you spot someone on the edge of the rice field. He really reminds you of someone. But who? That's it! He reminds you of that bartender on The Simpsons. What's his name? You think some more. What is it? <reading>Oh! Moe</reading> (おも) is his name!

meaning_mnemonic: The <radical>sun</radical> that gives <radical>life</radical> is our very own <kanji>star</kanji> (which we happen to call the sun). Of course, all the other stars are probably giving life to other planets as well.
reading_mnemonic: "All these life-giving <kanji>star</kanji>s need a protector," you say, pulling out your <reading>sa</reading>ber (せい). It's a big responsibility, but with your trusty saber in hand, you're sure you can defend our star system.

meaning_mnemonic: A <radical>tsunami</radical> of <radical>tongue</radical>s is coming at you. As it washes over you, you feel each individual tongue moving around on your body, licking you. They make you feel so... <kanji>lively</kanji>!
reading_mnemonic: This <kanji>lively</kanji> feeling isn't just happening to you, the tongue tsunami is licking it into all of the <reading>cats</reading> (かつ) in your neighborhood too!

meaning_mnemonic: A <radical>tsunami</radical> is coming, so you point your <radical>gun</radical> out the <radical>window</radical> at it. "You better turn back, <kanji>sea</kanji>, or I'll shoot!"
reading_mnemonic: The <kanji>sea</kanji> decides it doesn't want to die today, so it turns its tsunami around and goes the other way. You hop in your <reading>kay</reading>ak (かい) and chase after it with your gun, to make sure it actually returns to the sea and doesn't just drown someone else.

meaning_mnemonic: Your <radical>fortune</radical> <radical>boil</radical>s down to a single <kanji>point</kanji> in time. One point in time determines how the rest of your future will go.
reading_mnemonic: As you stare at the <kanji>point</kanji>, you watch in awe as it moves to the <reading>ten</reading> (てん) spot in a long series of numbers.

meaning_mnemonic: You scoop some <radical>grain</radical>s into a <radical>ladle</radical> to do <kanji>science</kanji>. You're doing experiments on these grains in your science <kanji>course</kanji>.
reading_mnemonic: Using your <kanji>science</kanji> skills, the right temperatures and measurements, you manage to get these grains to grow into a <reading>ca</reading>r (か). This is the science <kanji>department</kanji>'s special car now!

meaning_mnemonic: If you can steal the <radical>flowers</radical> that adorn a <radical>hat</radical> worn by an <radical>angel</radical>, you can use them to make delicious <kanji>tea</kanji>. Naturally, angels decorate their hats with only the most aromatic and delicious flowers fit for brewing.
reading_mnemonic: After brewing the <kanji>tea</kanji>, you look at the hat again and find a nametag inside that says <reading>Cha</reading>d (ちゃ). You decide that from now on this tea variety will be known as Chad tea, in honor of Chad.

meaning_mnemonic: The radical for <radical>eat</radical> and the kanji for <kanji>eat</kanji> are the same! Lucky you.
reading_mnemonic: Thank goodness, you finally get to <kanji>eat</kanji> your <kanji>meal</kanji>. You're so hungry. Someone has been starving you and now they've finally given you food. Unfortunately, though, every time you take a bite, you get a <reading>shock</reading> (しょく) from somewhere.

meaning_mnemonic: The radical <radical>neck</radical> and the kanji <kanji>neck</kanji> are exactly the same!
reading_mnemonic: The only thing you do with your <kanji>neck</kanji> is use it to swallow lots of <reading>coo</reading>l <reading>bea</reading>ns (くび). Mm mm. Feel those cool, cool beans sliding down your neck. You don't really taste them, but you know they're there.

meaning_mnemonic: The <radical>house</radical> radical makes up the <kanji>house</kanji> kanji! Pretty easy. This kanji is also used to mean <kanji>home</kanji>, so try to remember that too.
reading_mnemonic: What do you do in your <kanji>house</kanji>? You <reading>ea</reading>t <reading>e</reading>ggs (いえ), that's what. You eat eggs three times a day, every day. You really love eating eggs in your <kanji>home</kanji>!

meaning_mnemonic: The radical <radical>death</radical> and the kanji <kanji>death</kanji> are the same.
reading_mnemonic: Your <kanji>death</kanji> will be because of a <reading>bow</reading>ling (ぼう) accident. Oh, you didn't know? You're going to be hit by a giant bowling ball and crushed flat.

meaning_mnemonic:
Your <radical>private</radical> <radical>grain</radical>s are meant to stay <kanji>private</kanji>! You shouldn't be sharing them with the whole town, they're just for you.

This kanji also means <kanji>I</kanji>. Why? Because what's more private than you? I mean, I! Basically, some things are only the business of you (I) and those things should be private.
reading_mnemonic: You're getting into the zone, thinking about yourself (<kanji>I</kanji>) and how much you love having things that are <kanji>private</kanji> and just yours, when you realize there is a <reading>shee</reading>p (し) in this grain bag. And it's eating all of your (I's) private grains. No!

meaning_mnemonic: There's an <radical>ear</radical> just sitting on a <radical>stool</radical>. Nobody's watching, so, you <kanji>take</kanji> it.
reading_mnemonic: You're the kind of person who likes <vocabulary>to take</vocabulary> things. "What things?" you ask. Little <reading>toe</reading>s (と). Because that isn't creepy.

examples.en: It's about one thousand.

meaning_mnemonic:
If you have <kanji>one</kanji> <kanji>thousand</kanji>, you have... <vocabulary>one thousand</vocabulary>.

Simply saying 千 is the most common way to say 1,000, but sometimes you might use 一千 to emphasize or clarify the exact number.
reading_mnemonic: This is a jukugo word, which usually means on'yomi readings from the kanji. If you know the readings of your kanji you'll know how to read this as well. The only thing that's a bit weird is the reading of the 一. The ち turns into a small っ, making the reading for this word <reading>いっせん</reading>.

examples.ja: 元のポジションは、もっと北でした。

examples.ja: 元フィットネストレーナーです。

examples.en: Please correct it to the original data.
examples.ja: 元のデータに正して下さいね。

meaning_mnemonic: The kanji and the word are exactly the same. That means they share meanings as well. When it's used as a prefix, it takes on the related meaning of <vocabulary>ex-</vocabulary> or <vocabulary>former</vocabulary>.
reading_mnemonic:
Since this word is made up of a single kanji, it should use the kun'yomi reading. When learning the kanji, you didn't learn that reading, so here's a mnemonic to help you with this word: 

You're trying to trace a person back to their origin so you can learn more about them. You finally get there - it's a castle. The problem is that it's surrounded by a huge <reading>moat</reading> (もと) and you can't get past it because the drawbridge is up. Feel the frustration of this. Think about your goal and how close you are to getting to it if it wasn't for this lousy moat.

examples.en: These threads break off easily.
examples.ja: この糸は、すぐに切れる。

examples.en: We are out of toilet paper.
examples.ja: トイレットペーパーが切れた。

examples.en: This sword is very sharp.
examples.ja: この刀はとても切れる。

meaning_mnemonic:
This word consists of kanji with hiragana attached. Because the hiragana ends with an う sound, you know this word is a verb.

This is an intransitive verb. That means it does not take a direct object. The kanji means <kanji>cut</kanji> so this generally means that something is cut. Something breaks or snaps. No direct object here. That's why this verb means <vocabulary>to be cut</vocabulary> or <vocabulary>to snap</vocabulary>. Another meaning of this verb is <vocabulary>to expire</vocabulary> or <vocabulary>to run out</vocabulary>. This could be various things like your passport, or a deadline for an assignment.
reading_mnemonic:
Since this word consists of a kanji with hiragana attached, you can bet that it will use the kun'yomi reading. Here's a refresher to help you remember the  き portion of this word: 

Something is <vocabulary>snap</vocabulary>ping. Turns out that something is your arm. Your arm is a <reading>木</reading> (き) that grew out of you one day. "What's this ki doing here?" you ask. Then it suddenly <vocabulary>break</vocabulary>s in half! "OW OW OW! My ki! It's been cut!!"

examples.ja: タイトルは、全て大文字でおねがいします。

meaning_mnemonic: You have <kanji>big</kanji> <kanji>writing</kanji> <kanji>letters</kanji>. What do you think these are? THAT WOULD HAVE TO BE <vocabulary>UPPERCASE LETTERS</vocabulary>, RIGHT? Whoops, sorry, caps lock was on for a moment, there.
reading_mnemonic:
This is a jukugo word, which usually means on'yomi readings from the kanji. However, 大 uses the kun'yomi reading and 文 is an exception here, so here's a mnemonic to help you remember this:

Whenever you see an <vocabulary>uppercase letter</vocabulary>, you shout "<reading>おお</reading>, <reading>Moe</reading>!" (おおも). Your buddy Moe taught you the letters in the first place, so when you get stuck, you yell for him to come help you. And he always does. What a good guy.

meaning_mnemonic:
You feel your <kanji>ear</kanji> getting… <kanji>hit</kanji>? This is the feeling of a <vocabulary>whisper in</vocabulary> your <vocabulary>ear</vocabulary>; perhaps a secret, or some other confidential tidbit of information. Whatever it is it has impact, which is why it feels like a hit!

Note that this word is more often used in writing than in casual speech.

You cut yourself and there's <vocabulary>blood</vocabulary> everywhere. You need to stop the bleeding with something, but the only thing nearby is a block of <reading>chee</reading>se. examples.en: Which country are you from?

meaning_mnemonic: The <kanji>middle</kanji> <kanji>country</kanji>... who could that be? Let's think about it. Who invented kanji and therefore probably thinks they're the middle of the world? Who also is just a huge country that ruled much of Asia? That would be none other than <vocabulary>China</vocabulary>.

meaning_mnemonic: This is <kanji>heaven</kanji> <kanji>country</kanji>. Where is that? Probably just in <vocabulary>heaven</vocabulary> (or if you want to be fancy, the <vocabulary>kingdom of heaven</vocabulary>).
reading_mnemonic: This is a jukugo word, which usually means on'yomi readings from the kanji. If you know the readings of your kanji you'll know how to read this as well. The 国 is changed to the reading ごく though because of rendaku. Even heaven changes a little bit.

reading_mnemonic: This is a jukugo word that uses the on'yomi readings of the kanji. You've learned them already, so you should be able to read this on your own!

meaning_mnemonic: An <kanji>outside</kanji> <kanji>country</kanji> is one outside of your own country. That is a <vocabulary>foreign country</vocabulary>, <vocabulary>other countries</vocabulary>, or <vocabulary>overseas</vocabulary>.
reading_mnemonic: This is a jukugo word, which usually means on'yomi readings from the kanji. If you know the readings of your kanji you'll know how to read this as well.

examples.ja: お父さんだって、外国に行ったら「外国人」になるんだよ。

meaning_mnemonic: You know 外人 the word that means "foreigner," but that word is a bit informal and can come off as rude. The nicer, more politically correct version of the word is the one above. An <kanji>outside</kanji> <kanji>country</kanji> <kanji>person</kanji>. To differentiate this from "foreigner" we're going to use the more polite English version of this word as well (just like in Japanese): <vocabulary>Foreign Person</vocabulary>.
reading_mnemonic:

meaning_mnemonic:

reading_mnemonic: This is a jukugo word, which usually means on'yomi readings from the kanji. If you know the readings of your kanji you'll know how to read this as well.

examples.en: Tea, please.
examples.ja: お茶下さい。

examples.en: Last year, there was a tea tree here.
examples.ja: ここには去年、お茶の木が生えていました。

examples.en: Do British people often drink tea in the afternoon?
examples.ja: イギリス人はよく午後にお茶をのむんですか？

meaning_mnemonic: The お just makes the word more polite. Since tea is so important in Japan, it gets the お. Otherwise, you should be able to figure out the meaning as it's the same as the kanji.
reading_mnemonic: The reading is the on'yomi reading, just like you learned with the kanji.

examples.en: My bag is brown.
examples.ja: 私のカバンは茶色です。

examples.en: Brown haired cows are for restaurants.
examples.ja: 茶色の毛の牛はレストラン用です。

examples.en: I'd like to color my hair bright brown.
examples.ja: 明るい茶色にカラーリングしたいんですけど。

meaning_mnemonic: What is the <kanji>color</kanji> of <kanji>tea</kanji>? You'd think it would be green, assuming it's Japanese... but this word came from China. What color is Chinese tea? It tends to be more <vocabulary>brown</vocabulary>. Think Oolong tea, for example.
reading_mnemonic: The readings for both kanji are the readings you learned with the kanji, meaning you should be able to read this already.

examples.en: I eat donuts every day.
examples.ja: 毎日ドーナッツを食べる。

examples.en: I only had a bite of pineapple.
examples.ja: 私は、パイナップルを一口だけ食べました。

examples.en: Our dog often eats cat food.
examples.ja: うちの犬はキャットフードを食べることが多いです。

meaning_mnemonic: This word consists of kanji with hiragana attached. Because the hiragana ends with an う sound, you know this word is a verb. The kanji itself means <kanji>eat</kanji> so the verb version is <vocabulary>to eat</vocabulary>.
reading_mnemonic: You have to remember the た portion if you want to be able to read this word, which uses the kun'yomi reading. Think about yourself <vocabulary>eat</vocabulary>ing some <reading>ta</reading>cos (た). Imagine yourself eating it, that raw beef taste in your mouth (either like it or hate it).

examples.en: Let's stretch your neck.
examples.ja: 首のストレッチをしましょう。

examples.en: Giraffes have a long neck.
examples.ja: キリンは首が長いです。

examples.en: My mother always wears a scarf around her neck.
examples.ja: 母は、いつも首にスカーフをつけています。

meaning_mnemonic: The kanji and the word are exactly the same. That means they share meanings as well.
reading_mnemonic: You learned the reading for this word via the kanji, so you should be able to read this word just fine.

examples.en: Let's stretch your ankle.
examples.ja: 足首のストレッチをしましょう。

examples.en: I wore high heels and my ankles became sore.
examples.ja: ハイヒールをはいて、足首がいたくなった。

examples.en: When you hike on a large mountain, don't injure your ankle.
examples.ja: 大きい山でハイキングするときは、足首をケガしないようにね。

meaning_mnemonic: What is the <kanji>neck</kanji> of your <kanji>leg</kanji>? Think about it. It's your <vocabulary>ankle</vocabulary>.
reading_mnemonic: This word uses the kun'yomi readings from both kanji, probably because it includes body parts. You know the kun'yomi reading of 足 from previous vocab and you know the kun'yomi reading of 首 from learning that kanji. So, you should be able to read this kanji so long as you remember that it's all kun'yomi.

examples.en: Last month, I was fired from the company.
examples.ja: 先月、会社を首になりました。

examples.en: I will try my best not to get fired.
examples.ja: 首にならないように、がんばります。

examples.en: If you do such a thing, you'll lose your part-time job!
examples.ja: そんなことしたら、バイト首になるよ！

meaning_mnemonic: The になる part means "to become," so literally this means "to become neck." If you think about it, when something becomes neck, it has to do with you getting your head cut off (at the neck). But, in today's modern society we don't do that too often. Instead, this means you lose your job, aka <vocabulary>to get fired</vocabulary>.
reading_mnemonic: This word contains the reading you learned with the kanji. Everything else is hiragana.

examples.en: My house is near a mountain.
examples.ja: 私の家は山の近くにあります。

examples.en: Secondhand houses are very popular in the United States.
examples.ja: アメリカでは中古の家がとても人気です。

examples.en: Sorry, I haven't left home yet.
examples.ja: すいません、まだ家を出てないんです。

meaning_mnemonic: The kanji and the word are exactly the same. That means they share meanings as well.
reading_mnemonic:
Since this word is made up of a single kanji, it probably uses the kun'yomi reading. You learned this reading with the kanji. But there's a second reading you haven't learned yet, so here's a mnemonic for both:

What do you do in your <vocabulary>house</vocabulary>? You <reading>ea</reading>t <reading>e</reading>ggs (いえ). You love to eat eggs at <vocabulary>home</vocabulary>. But it has to be on the 内 (うち), a.k.a. the inside, of your house. For some reason you can only eat eggs in the 内 of your house.

Both readings relate to house and home, but いえ is a bit more for the physical building (the house) while うち is more for your personal sense of home, including your family and household.

examples.en: My father is 42 years old.
examples.ja: 父は、四十二才です。

examples.en: That building is about 42 meters tall.
examples.ja: あのビルは、およそ四十二メートルです。

examples.en: The hotel room number is forty-two.
examples.ja: ホテルのルームナンバーは四十二です。

meaning_mnemonic:
Four tens plus two. That equals <vocabulary>forty two</vocabulary>. 

P.S. Please don't panic. "<vocabulary>The Answer</vocabulary>" is NOT a correct answer for this. It is just a reference to the greatest book of all time. Sorry for the confusion and so long and thanks for all the fish.
reading_mnemonic: This is a jukugo word, which usually means on'yomi readings from the kanji. But! Don't forget, 四 uses the kun'yomi reading, since the on'yomi reading sounds too much like the word for "death."

examples.en: Last year, my mother died.
examples.ja: 去年、母が亡くなった。

examples.en: This is a flower for my friend who has passed away.
examples.ja: これは、亡くなった友人のための花です。

examples.en: My sister said "the lottery..." before her death.
examples.ja: 姉は、亡くなる前に「宝くじ...」と言いました。

meaning_mnemonic: This word consists of kanji with hiragana attached. Because the hiragana ends with an う sound, you know this word is a verb. This word is actually two words put together, though. 亡く means "be deceased." なる means "to become." So put that all together and you have <vocabulary>to pass away</vocabulary> or <vocabulary>to become deceased</vocabulary>. It's basically a polite way to say something died (死ぬ).
reading_mnemonic:
To learn to read this kanji you have to remember the な part of 亡く, though our mnemonic will use the whole thing.

If you're about to become deceased, you are probably <reading>knock</reading>ing (なく) on death's door.

examples.en: Please enter your email address in all lowercase letters.
examples.ja: Eメールアドレスは、全て小文字で入力して下さい。

examples.en: Please use lowercase letters and uppercase letters in the password.
examples.ja: パスワードには小文字と大文字を入れて下さい。

examples.en: Is this a lowercase L? Or is it a capital letter I?
examples.ja: これは小文字のLですか？それとも大文字のIですか？

meaning_mnemonic: You know that 文字 means "letters". So, what are "small letters"? That would be <vocabulary>lowercase letters</vocabulary>.
reading_mnemonic:
This is a jukugo word, which usually means on'yomi readings from the kanji. However, 小 uses the kun'yomi reading and 文 is an exception here, so here's a mnemonic to help you remember this:

You learned your lowercase letters from <reading>子</reading> <reading>Moe</reading> (こも). That's right, after Moe taught you all the letters, his son 子 Moe taught you the lowercase ones. Such teamwork.

examples.en: November and December are winter vacation.
examples.ja: 十一月と十二月は、冬休みです。

examples.en: There are no big plans during winter vacation.
examples.ja: 冬休みには、大したプランはありません。

examples.en: Every year during winter vacation, I go to Mexico.
examples.ja: 冬休みは毎年、メキシコに行きます。

meaning_mnemonic: The <kanji>winter</kanji> <kanji>rest</kanji>! Wait, nobody calls it that. This is a <vocabulary>winter holiday</vocabulary> or <vocabulary>winter break</vocabulary>.
reading_mnemonic: The readings for these are both the kun'yomi readings. Hopefully you learned them when you were doing vocab in the previous levels so that all you have to do now is combine the two separate words into one bigger word. Please don't take a winter break until you figure this word out.

examples.en: I was finally able to pass JLPT N1.
examples.ja: やっとJLPTN1にごうかくすることが出来ました。

examples.en: Dinner's ready!
examples.ja: ディナーが出来たよ。

examples.en: Mochi are made from rice.
examples.ja: もちは米から出来る。

meaning_mnemonic:
When you <kanji>exit</kanji> and <kanji>come</kanji>, apparently it means <vocabulary>to be able to do</vocabulary>. I think of it like you're leaving a location (出) to do a task and then you come (来る) back after you did it. Perhaps you were waiting in a room training like someone from Dragonball. When you leave the room, you are ready to fight the enemy and win. You train in that room <vocabulary>to be able to do</vocabulary> whatever you need to do, and only leave and come back alive because you were able to do it.

This verb is really common and it has a wide range of meanings. It can also mean things like <vocabulary>to be ready</vocabulary>, for example a meal, and <vocabulary>to be made</vocabulary>, for example when saying what something is made from. It's commonly written in hiragana, but you'll see the kanji version too!
reading_mnemonic: The readings are a bit strange. They're both kun'yomi readings, where 出 is で and 来る is きる. This is different from the reading you originally learned with 来る (くる), though, so be careful. If you can remember that and remember the kun'yomi readings from the previous vocab, you should be able to learn this one's reading as well.

examples.en: How do you say "thanks" in the dialect of this area?
examples.ja: このエリアの方言で「ありがとう」は何と言いますか？

examples.en: In this country, dialects are cherished.
examples.ja: この国では方言がとても大切にされています。

examples.en: Learning Japanese dialects is valuing Japanese culture.
examples.ja: 日本の方言を学ぶことは、日本文化を大切にすることです。

meaning_mnemonic:
The <kanji>way</kanji> you <kanji>say</kanji> things is your <vocabulary>dialect</vocabulary>. It's an entire "way" of speaking. 

You can even think of the  方 as being a "direction." If you go far enough in different directions in a country, you'll discover different regional dialects.
reading_mnemonic: This is a jukugo word that uses the on'yomi readings of the kanji. You should be able to read this on your own.

examples.en: My brother is very fast talker.
examples.ja: 兄は、とても早口です。

examples.en: I spoke fast when I made an order, so I got five beers instead of one.
examples.ja: 早口でオーダーしたので、生ビールが一つの代わりに五つ来た。

examples.en: Many Japanese are good at fast-talking.
examples.ja: 日本人は、早口が上手な人が多いですね。

meaning_mnemonic: When you have a <kanji>fast</kanji> <kanji>mouth</kanji>, you're probably a <vocabulary>fast talker</vocabulary>, right motormouth?
reading_mnemonic: Remember how body parts often change even jukugo words to kun'yomi readings? That's what happened here too. Both readings are kun'yomi, making this one <reading>はやくち</reading>.

examples.en: I’m ten yen short.
examples.ja: お金が十円足りないんです。

examples.en: We are one onion short.
examples.ja: 玉ねぎが一つ足りない。

examples.en: I don't have enough strength to raise this sofa to the loft.
examples.ja: このソファをロフトに上げるには力が足りない。

meaning_mnemonic: You know the word 足りる from Level 4. What is this one? it's the opposite (negative form on a verb is ない). So, what is the opposite of 足りる (To be sufficient)? The opposite is <vocabulary>to not be sufficient</vocabulary> or <vocabulary>not enough</vocabulary>.
reading_mnemonic: The reading is the same as 足りる (たりる) which you should have seen in Level 4.

examples.en: My former partner is older than me.
examples.ja: 元パートナーは、私より年上です。

examples.en: My brother is three years older than you.
examples.ja: 私の兄は、あなたより三才年上ですよ。

examples.en: I went on a date with an older woman.
examples.ja: 年上の女の人とデートに行った。

meaning_mnemonic: When you're <kanji>year</kanji>s <kanji>above</kanji> someone else, you are <vocabulary>older</vocabulary> than that person.
reading_mnemonic: The reading for this one is an exception, because it uses kun'yomi readings even though it is a jukugo kanji. You already know the separate kun'yomi readings from the vocabulary of the last level, but you will have to remember to actually use this knowledge when this word comes up.

examples.en: I want to be on a diet this year.
examples.ja: 今年はダイエットをしたいです。

examples.en: My child will be a freshman in college this year.
examples.ja: 私の子は、今年、大学一年生になります。

examples.en: I just came to Japan in April of this year.
examples.ja: 今年の四月に日本へ来たばかりです。

meaning_mnemonic: The <kanji>now</kanji> <kanji>year</kanji> is which year? It is <vocabulary>this year</vocabulary>.
reading_mnemonic:
The reading for 今年 (ことし) is kinda weird, what with the こ part and all. Just imagine the こん reading you learned for 今 has been shortened to こ here, if that helps. Then the 年 part uses its kun'yomi reading とし. It's an odd combo, so here's a mnemonic:

Your goal <vocabulary>this year</vocabulary> is to treat everyone with <reading>courtesy</reading> (ことし). You're going to be nice and polite to everyone this year, even on social media. After all, there's too much negativity in the world right now. Oh yes, no doubt about it — this year will be one of courtesy.

examples.en: This class has many younger children.
examples.ja: このクラスは年下の子が多いです。

examples.en: I went on a date with a younger boy.
examples.ja: 年下の男の子とデートに行きました。

examples.en: I am ten years younger than my sister.
examples.ja: 私は、姉よりも十才年下です。

meaning_mnemonic: When you have someone who has <kanji>years</kanji> <kanji>below</kanji> your own, this person is <vocabulary>younger</vocabulary> than you.
reading_mnemonic: The reading for this one is kind of strange. It is the kun'yomi reading for both of the kanji. You know the kun'yomi readings from earlier, back when you learned the vocab 年 and 下.

examples.en: Is there a convenience store at the east exit?
examples.ja: 東口にはコンビニがありますか？

examples.en: Buses leave from the east exit.
examples.ja: バスは東口から出ます。

examples.en: Let's meet at the east exit.
examples.ja: 東口で会いましょう。

meaning_mnemonic: Remember 北口 and 西口 from a few levels before? This is the <kanji>east</kanji> version of that, so it means <vocabulary>east exit</vocabulary> or <vocabulary>east entrance</vocabulary>.
reading_mnemonic: Just like 北口 and 西口, this also uses kun'yomi readings. And just like before, watch out for the rendaku that changes くち to ぐち!

examples.en: Turn this way, please.
examples.ja: こっちを向いてください。

examples.en: When you look down, you can see a large river.
examples.ja: 下を向くと、大きい川が見えます。

examples.en: The house faces west, so it gets nice sunlight in the afternoon.
examples.ja: 家は西に向いていて、午後は日当たりがいいです。

meaning_mnemonic:
You know that the kanji means <kanji>yonder</kanji>, which is like "over there." This is the verb version of "yonder." That being said, "to yonder" isn't really a thing, so you have to think of what happens when you "look yonder." This word means <vocabulary>to turn toward</vocabulary> or <vocabulary>to face</vocabulary>. You're looking yonder, but you have to turn towards said yonder to look that way.

This word can also mean <vocabulary>to be suitable</vocabulary>, as in a good fit for a job, role, or situation. After all, you turn toward the things you're most suitable for, right?
reading_mnemonic:
Since this word consists of a kanji with hiragana attached, you can bet that it will use the kun'yomi reading. You didn't learn that reading with this kanji, so here's a mnemonic to help you: 

You turn <vocabulary>to face</vocabulary> a new direction and look out into the distance. There is a single cow out there. It turns to face you too, and says <reading>moo</reading> (む).

examples.en: North Carolina is located in east of the United States.
examples.ja: ノースカロライナはアメリカの東にあります。

examples.en: If you go east from here, there is a river.
examples.ja: ここから東へ行くと、川がありますよ。

examples.en: Then, please turn to the east.
examples.ja: それでは、東の方を向いて下さい。

meaning_mnemonic: The kanji and the word are exactly the same. That means they share meanings as well.
reading_mnemonic:
Since this word is made up of a single kanji, it should use the kun'yomi reading. You learned that reading with the kanji, but here's a mnemonic refresher just in case:

You see a man walk straight toward the sun rising in the <kanji>east</kanji>. It's so bright he can't see anything, so he trips and <reading>he gash</reading>es (ひがし) his knee on a rock. Yikes… But he gets back up, determined to head east, and, oh no, he gashes his other knee! OK, he should probably give up on going east.

examples.en: I am English.
examples.ja: 私は、イギリス人です。

examples.en: That's my draft beer.
examples.ja: それは、私の生ビールです。

examples.en: Please let me join the WaniKani Level 60 club.
examples.ja: どうか私をワニカニレベル六十の会に入れて下さい。

meaning_mnemonic: The kanji and the word are exactly the same. That means they share meanings as well.
reading_mnemonic: If you're lucky, you already know this (very) common word's reading. It's the word for "I," probably one of the first things you'd learn in Japanese. The reading for this is わたし. If you don't know that already, just think: "<reading>What, a し</reading>?" referring to the reading of the kanji, which is し.

examples.en: Stress from my private life is big.
examples.ja: 私生活のストレスが大きい。

examples.en: Koichi doesn't tell his friends or others about his personal life.
examples.ja: コウイチは、私生活のことを友人にも他人にもあまり言わない。

examples.en: She's a model, but in her personal life, she's a mother of three children.
examples.ja: いつもはモデルですが、私生活では三人の子の母です。

meaning_mnemonic: You've seen 生活 before, right? So what about the "life" of <kanji>I</kanji>? Whose life is that? Why, that's my own <vocabulary>personal life</vocabulary>.
reading_mnemonic: This is a jukugo word, which usually means on'yomi readings from the kanji. If you know the readings of your kanji you'll know how to read this as well.

examples.en: I want to join a private university.
examples.ja: 私立の大学に入りたいです。

examples.en: International schools in Japan are mainly private.
examples.ja: 日本のインターナショナルスクールは主に私立です。

examples.en: Are you perhaps a first grade student of the private school, WaniKani Academy?
examples.ja: もしかして私立ワニカニアカデミーの一年生ですか？

meaning_mnemonic:
<kanji>I</kanji> am the one who keeps this place <kanji>stand</kanji>ing. In other words, it's a <vocabulary>private</vocabulary> establishment — <vocabulary>privately-run</vocabulary> and <vocabulary>privately-operated</vocabulary> by ME!

私立 means "private" in the sense of a business, school, or other institution that's run by a private entity, rather than by the government or the state.
reading_mnemonic:
This is a jukugo word, which usually means on'yomi readings from the kanji. If you know the readings of your kanji you'll know how to read this as well.

Both 市立 (municipal) and 私立 (private) are pronounced as しりつ and it's hard to tell them apart when speaking. Although they're not official readings, people sometimes distinguish 市立 and 私立 by pronouncing them as いちりつ and わたくしりつ respectively.

examples.en: You take them one at a time, okay?
examples.ja: 一つずつ取るんですよ。

examples.en: I finally got my license!
examples.ja: やっとライセンスが取れました！

examples.en: Can you get a mug from there for me?
examples.ja: そこからマグカップを取ってくれない？

meaning_mnemonic: This word consists of kanji with hiragana attached. Because the hiragana ends with an う sound, you know this word is a verb. The kanji itself means <kanji>take</kanji>, so the verb version is <vocabulary>to take something</vocabulary>.
reading_mnemonic: Since this word has okurigana (hiragana attached to the kanji) you know that it's probably going to be the kun'yomi reading. You already know this kun'yomi reading, so you should be able to read this word.

examples.en: Can you spread both of your legs more?
examples.ja: 両足、もっと広がる？

examples.en: The living room spreads from this entrance.
examples.ja: リビングルームは、この入り口から広がります。

examples.en: The virus quickly spread to all Japan.
examples.ja: ウィルスは、すぐに全日本に広がった。

meaning_mnemonic: Remember 広い? Well this is like that, except a verb. When something does the action of getting wide, it means to spread out, to extend, or to stretch. You already learned 広げる, which is used when you spread SOMETHING. But 広がる is intransitive, so it doesn't take a direct object. Like: The sea spreads out before you. See? No direct object. Actually, verbs ending in okurigana that rhyme with ある tend to be intransitive like this. You can remember this because if something is ある, it's just there, existing, not acting on anything else. That's why verbs that sound like it are often intransitive too!
reading_mnemonic: The reading is the same as 広い, too, so as long as you knew that you knew this reading as well.

examples.en: I do not eat pork.
examples.ja: 私は豚肉を食べません。

examples.en: Pork is cheap today.
examples.ja: 今日は豚肉が安いです。

examples.en: Pork is rich in vitamin B₁.
examples.ja: 豚肉にはビタミンB₁がたっぷり入っています。

examples.en: First, we are going to start by sprinkling some Krazy Salt on the pork.
examples.ja: まず、豚肉にクレイジーソルトをふりかけます。

examples.en: I might have gotten food poisoning from the pork I had for lunch.
examples.ja: ランチに食べた豚肉に当たったかもしれません。

meaning_mnemonic: A <kanji>pig</kanji>'s <kanji>meat</kanji> is called <vocabulary>pork</vocabulary>.
reading_mnemonic: The readings are the ones you learned with the kanji.

examples.en: Mt. Fuji is one of the national treasures in Japan.
examples.ja: ふじ山は日本の国宝の一つです。

examples.en: I want this hotel to be a national treasure someday.
examples.ja: このホテルを、いつか国宝にしてほしいです。

examples.en: "Why is this hair dryer a national treasure?" "Because Nicholas Cage kissed it."
examples.ja: 「何でこのヘアドライヤーは国宝なんですか？」「ニコラス・ケイジがキスしたからだよ」

meaning_mnemonic: A <kanji>country</kanji>'s <kanji>treasure</kanji> is their <vocabulary>national treasure</vocabulary>.
reading_mnemonic: This is a jukugo word that uses the on'yomi readings of the kanji. You should be able to read this on your own.

examples.en: The lottery is available on the Internet.
examples.ja: 宝くじはインターネットで手に入ります。

examples.en: "My sister won the lottery." "That's amazing! How much?" "10,000 yen."
examples.ja: 「妹が宝くじに当たったのよ。」「すごいね！で、いくら？」「一万円。」

examples.en: Yamashita-sensei had won a million yen lottery. He stopped coming to class the next day.
examples.ja: 百万円の宝くじが当たった山下先生。次の日からクラスに来なくなった。

meaning_mnemonic: 宝 is a <kanji>treasure</kanji>. くじ is a lottery. So if you have a treasure lottery (you win treasure if you win the lottery) then you have yourself a <vocabulary>lottery</vocabulary>.
reading_mnemonic: The reading uses the 宝 vocab reading, たから.

examples.en: The goal is one step away.
examples.ja: あと一歩でゴールです。

examples.en: I go up one step at a time.
examples.ja: 一歩ずつ上がっていきます。

examples.en: Step back, please.
examples.ja: 一歩、後ろに下がってください。

meaning_mnemonic: If <kanji>歩</kanji> is "walk" and you take <kanji>one</kanji> <kanji>walk</kanji>, then really you are just taking <vocabulary>one step</vocabulary>. When there's a number before 歩, it refers to the number of steps you're taking. The most common is this one, and you'll see it on urinals when they kindly ask you to please take one step forward because peeing isn't a game and somebody has to clean up after you.
reading_mnemonic: The reading is pretty standard in its trickiness. The いち shortens to an いっ and the ほ rendakus to ぽ. One step at a time, right?

examples.en: It's 300 yen.
examples.ja: 三百円です。

examples.en: About 300 people came.
examples.ja: 大体三百人が来ました。

examples.en: A year is 365 days.
examples.ja: 一年は三百六十五日です。

meaning_mnemonic: You have <kanji>three</kanji> <kanji>hundred</kanji>s. What does that come out to? <vocabulary>Three hundred</vocabulary>.
reading_mnemonic: The reading is a little bit weird, so be careful. You should already know the on'yomi readings, but the ひゃく rendakus to びゃく. This pattern will repeat itself with 三 + many counter kanjis that can rendaku, so pay attention for it as you read Japanese.

examples.en: If you add 1 to 1, that'll be 2.
examples.ja: 一に一を足すと、二になります。

examples.en: Maybe it would be better to add more water to this soup.
examples.ja: このスープ、もう少し水を足した方がいいんじゃないかな。

examples.en: Let's add some white paint.
examples.ja: 白のペンキを足しましょう。

meaning_mnemonic:
Remember 足りる? That is "to be enough." How can you make something be enough? You keep adding things to the pile until you reach that point where there are enough! That's why this verb is <vocabulary>to add something</vocabulary>, because you keep adding things until you 足りる.

This verb is transitive, like most verbs ending in す, which is why you are adding something. It's not getting itself added all by itself. Maybe you add so much that someone tries to <reading>sue</reading> (す) you for that nasty pile of squirrels you keep outside.
reading_mnemonic: The reading is the same as 足りる, so if you know that you can add things up to this.

examples.en: This vehicle is big.
examples.ja: 車両は大きいですね。

examples.en: The vehicle entered the tunnel.
examples.ja: 車両はトンネルに入った。

examples.en: The train car ahead of this one is car No. 1.
examples.ja: 前の車両は一号車です。

meaning_mnemonic:
A <kanji>car</kanji> has wheels on <kanji>both</kanji> sides, and together they make a <vocabulary>vehicle</vocabulary>.

車両 is a formal word often used in official or technical contexts. It refers not just to standard cars but also to <vocabulary>train car</vocabulary>s and other vehicles that carry people or goods. You'll commonly see it in public transportation terms, on signs like "No vehicles allowed," or in driver's license and traffic law classifications.
reading_mnemonic: This is a jukugo word that uses the on'yomi readings of the kanji. You should be able to read this on your own.

examples.en: I go to work early on weekdays.
examples.ja: 平日は早く会社に行きます。

examples.en: I got an email three days earlier.
examples.ja: 三日も早くメールが来た。

examples.en: Please get plenty of rest and feel better soon.
examples.ja: ゆっくり休んで早くよくなってください。

meaning_mnemonic: This is the adverb version of the kanji <kanji>early</kanji>. It's a little thing you can begin sentences with to say you're doing something <vocabulary>early</vocabulary> or <vocabulary>quickly</vocabulary>.
reading_mnemonic: Since you already know the reading of the vocab word 早い, you should be able to read this word as well.

examples.en: Their death was too soon.
examples.ja: その死は早すぎました。

examples.en: Why are you not afraid of death?
examples.ja: どうして死がこわくないの？

examples.en: It is really tough to lose a pet.
examples.ja: ペットの死は本当につらいものだ。

meaning_mnemonic: The kanji and the word are exactly the same. That means they share meanings as well.
reading_mnemonic: This has the same reading as the kanji you learned, meaning you know the reading!

examples.en: My sister is in Singapore.
examples.ja: 姉はシンガポールにいます。

examples.en: My sister's dad and my dad are the same person.
examples.ja: 姉のお父さんと私のお父さんは同じ人です。

examples.en: I have two sisters and a brother, so we are siblings of four.
examples.ja: 二人の姉と、一人の兄がいるので、四人兄弟です。

meaning_mnemonic: The kanji and the word are exactly the same. That means they share meanings as well. This is your older sister, by the way. Not somebody else's.
reading_mnemonic:
Since this word is made up of a single kanji, it should use the kun'yomi reading. You haven't learned this reading yet,  so here's a mnemonic to help you remember:

Picture your <vocabulary>older sister</vocabulary> (even if you don't have one), her birthday is coming up and there's only one thing she wants from you. <reading>A ne</reading>cklace (あね). She's wanted a necklace for years and you're finally going to give her one. She'll be so happy.

examples.en: I knocked on the president's office.
examples.ja: 社長室をノックした。

examples.en: Is there a vacant room today?
examples.ja: 今日、空室はありますか？

examples.en: The woman's corpse was in one room of this hotel.
examples.ja: 女の死体があったのは、このホテルの一室だった。

meaning_mnemonic: You'll see this attached to other words... like "waiting" or "guest." When you see this, you'll know it is a ___ room, making this word mean <vocabulary>room</vocabulary> (same as the kanji).
reading_mnemonic: The reading is the on'yomi reading. Don't type the 〜 out when writing the answer. It's just there to let you know that there's usually something attached to this word.

examples.en: There was a large tree on the grassland.
examples.ja: 草地の上に大きな木があった。

examples.en: Ireland has many grasslands.
examples.ja: アイルランドにはたくさんの草地があります。

examples.en: Would you like to picnic on the grassland somewhere?
examples.ja: どこか草地でピクニックしませんか？

meaning_mnemonic: <kanji>Grass</kanji> covering the <kanji>earth</kanji> is a <vocabulary>meadow</vocabulary>. Or, if you're less creative, it's <vocabulary>grassland</vocabulary>.
reading_mnemonic: The reading is a combination of kun'yomi and on'yomi readings. That being said, both readings for both kanji are the readings you learned with the kanji so you should be able to read this.

examples.en: The current British king is Charles III.
examples.ja: 今のイギリスの国王はチャールズ三世です。

examples.en: There is no king in Japan.
examples.ja: 日本には国王がいません。

examples.en: I have performed in front of the king.
examples.ja: 国王の前でパフォーマンスをしたことがあります。

meaning_mnemonic: A <kanji>country</kanji> <kanji>king</kanji> is still a <vocabulary>king</vocabulary>, just of a bigger area.
reading_mnemonic: This is a jukugo word that uses the on'yomi readings of the kanji. You should be able to read this on your own.

examples.en: The moon is smaller than Mercury.
examples.ja: 月は、水星より小さい。

examples.en: Mercury does not have an atmosphere.
examples.ja: 水星には大気がありません。

examples.en: You can see Mercury in the west from the top of the mountain.
examples.ja: 山の上から西の方に水星を見ることができます。

meaning_mnemonic: The <kanji>water</kanji> <kanji>star</kanji> is the planet <vocabulary>Mercury</vocabulary>. That's where we hid all of our secret moon water. Mercury looks enough like our moon, so we put it there so no one could find it.
reading_mnemonic: This is a jukugo word that uses the on'yomi readings of the kanji. You should be able to read this on your own.

examples.en: What you can see there is Venus.
examples.ja: あそこに見えるのが、金星です。

examples.en: You can see a bright Venus in the night sky.
examples.ja: 夜の空に明るい金星が見える。

examples.en: Venus can be seen in the east before the sunrise and the west sky after the sunset.
examples.ja: 金星は、日の出前の東の空、または日が入った後の西の空に見ることが出来ます。

meaning_mnemonic: The <kanji>gold</kanji> <kanji>star</kanji> is <vocabulary>Venus</vocabulary>. It's the only planet in our solar system that's the same color as gold.
reading_mnemonic: This is a jukugo word that uses the on'yomi readings of the kanji. You should be able to read this on your own.

examples.en: Mushrooms grow on this tree.
examples.ja: この木にはキノコが生える。

examples.en: Santa Claus has a white beard.
examples.ja: サンタクロースには白いヒゲが生えています。

examples.en: There are many trees growing in the state of Oregon.
examples.ja: オレゴン州には、たくさんの木が生えています。

meaning_mnemonic: This word consists of kanji with hiragana attached. Because the hiragana ends with an う sound, you know this word is a verb. Remember how 生きる means "to live?" Well this is what happens right after it starts to live. It begins <vocabulary>to grow</vocabulary>!
reading_mnemonic:
Since this word consists of a kanji with hiragana attached, you can bet that it will use the kun'yomi reading. You didn't learn that reading with this kanji, so here's a mnemonic to help you: 

When something starts <vocabulary>to grow</vocabulary> it also learns to laugh. Imagine a little plant growing out of the ground laughing. "<reading>Ha</reading> (は) ha ha ha!" it says, as it sprouts out of the ground.

examples.en: Saturn is big.
examples.ja: 土星は大きいです。

examples.en: Do you know which one is Saturn?
examples.ja: どれが土星か、分かりますか。

examples.en: How can I get to Saturn?
examples.ja: 土星にはどうやって行けばいいですか？

meaning_mnemonic: The <kanji>ground</kanji> <kanji>star</kanji> is <vocabulary>Saturn</vocabulary>. That's why it's called "sat"urn. Because the first people to find it sat on the ground there. It's a star made completely of sit-on-able ground.
reading_mnemonic: This is a jukugo word that uses the on'yomi readings of the kanji. You should be able to read this on your own.

examples.en: This city is very lively.
examples.ja: この町は、とても活気があります。

examples.en: Thanks to Michael, liveliness was brought to the company.
examples.ja: マイケルのおかげで、会社に活気が生まれた。

examples.en: The farmers market is always full of life.
examples.ja: ファーマーズマーケットはいつも活気にあふれています。

meaning_mnemonic: If you have <kanji>lively</kanji> <kanji>energy</kanji> you have more than enough <vocabulary>energy</vocabulary> for everyone to start noticing. They come up to you and compliment you on your amazing <vocabulary>liveliness</vocabulary>.
reading_mnemonic: This is a jukugo word that uses the on'yomi readings of the kanji. You should be able to read this on your own. Just be careful because かつ is being shortened here to かっ. It's a pretty common change for on'yomi ending in つ, so keep your eyes open for more that do this!

examples.en: There are many insects underground.
examples.ja: 地中には、たくさんの虫がいます。

examples.en: There is a radar underground.
examples.ja: 地中にはレーダーがある。

examples.en: Dad, how's your life underground?
examples.ja: お父さん、地中の生活はどうですか？

meaning_mnemonic: If you're in the <kanji>middle</kanji> of the <kanji>ground</kanji>, then you're most likely <vocabulary>underground</vocabulary>. Are you a moleperson? That's pretty cool.
reading_mnemonic: This is a jukugo word that uses the on'yomi readings of the kanji. You should be able to read this on your own.

examples.en: Let's do some exercises to conjugate "deru."
examples.ja: 「出る」の活用のエクササイズをしましょう。

examples.en: I want to utilize rain water to build a pool for ducks.
examples.ja: 雨の水を活用してアヒルのためのプールを作りたい。

examples.en: I don’t know if I can put this data to good use.
examples.ja: このデータをうまく活用して、何かできないかな。

meaning_mnemonic:
If you make <kanji>lively</kanji> <kanji>use</kanji> of something, you're probably <vocabulary>utilizing</vocabulary> it or making <vocabulary>practical use</vocabulary> of it.

活用 means making full use of something. In the context of Japanese grammar, 活用 also refers to the <vocabulary>conjugation</vocabulary> of verbs and adjectives.
reading_mnemonic: This is a jukugo word that uses the on'yomi readings of the kanji. You should be able to read this on your own.

examples.en: My father will learn the news today.
examples.ja: 父は今日、そのニュースを知る。

examples.en: This time there were many people I didn't know at the party.
examples.ja: 今回のパーティには知らない人が多かった。

examples.en: Did you know that this koala is an artificial robot?
examples.ja: このコアラ、人工ロボットだって知ってた？

meaning_mnemonic: This word consists of kanji with hiragana attached. Because the hiragana ends with an う sound, you know this word is a verb. The kanji itself means <kanji>know</kanji> so the verb version means <vocabulary>to know</vocabulary>. It can additionally refer to how one comes to know something, so it also means <vocabulary>to learn</vocabulary> or <vocabulary>to find out</vocabulary>.
reading_mnemonic: Since this word consists of a kanji with hiragana attached, you can bet that it will use the kun'yomi reading. You learned this reading already with the kanji, so you're good to go! Yay!

examples.en: I have a bracelet on my wrist.
examples.ja: 手首にブレスレットをしています。

examples.en: This is a wrist stretch.
examples.ja: これは、手首のストレッチです。

examples.en: My husband has a tattoo on his wrist.
examples.ja: 私の主人は手首にタトゥーが有ります。

meaning_mnemonic: Your <kanji>hand</kanji>'s <kanji>neck</kanji> is your <vocabulary>wrist</vocabulary>!
reading_mnemonic: This word uses the kun'yomi readings from both kanji, probably because it includes body parts. You know them both already, so now you know this too!

examples.en: Are you going to the office alone today?
examples.ja: 今日は一人で出社ですか？

examples.en: I'm sorry, the president hasn't come to work yet.
examples.ja: すみません、社長はまだ出社してないんです。

examples.en: I went to a cafe before going to work.
examples.ja: 出社する前にカフェに行きました。

meaning_mnemonic: If you <kanji>exit</kanji> somewhere in order to go to your <kanji>company</kanji>, that's <vocabulary>going to the office</vocabulary>, <vocabulary>arriving at the office</vocabulary>, and <vocabulary>coming to work</vocabulary>.
reading_mnemonic: This is a jukugo word that uses the on'yomi readings of the kanji. You should be able to read this on your own. Just watch out for  the しゅつ, which gets changed to しゅっ, as many つs do in this situation.

examples.en: I got a text from my ex-partner.
examples.ja: 元パートナーからテキストがきた。

examples.en: Oh, it's the same as my ex-partner's necklace.
examples.ja: あ、それ、元パートナーのネックレスといっしょだ。

examples.en: This is a video of me skiing with my ex-partner at Mt. Fuji.
examples.ja: これは、ふじ山で元パートナーとスキーをしたときのビデオだよ。

meaning_mnemonic:
Your <kanji>origin</kanji> partner is a partner you had originally, but don't have anymore. In other words, this is your <vocabulary>ex-partner</vocabulary> or <vocabulary>former partner</vocabulary>.

Like in English, this word is fairly formal, and it covers any kind of ex-partner, including business and romantic partners.
reading_mnemonic: This uses the kun'yomi of 元 and then it's just kana, so you should know how to read this!

examples.en: An orange stone entered the river.
examples.ja: オレンジ色の石ころが川に入った。

examples.en: There are a lot of pebbles on this beach.
examples.ja: このビーチ、石ころがたくさんあるね。

examples.en: There are many pebbles in front of the entrance.
examples.ja: 入り口の前は石ころが多いです。

meaning_mnemonic: You've already learned 石, which means <kanji>stone</kanji>. You haven't seen ころ before, but it's sometimes used as a casual suffix for small, round things. Put the two together, and you've got a <vocabulary>small stone</vocabulary>, or <vocabulary>pebble</vocabulary>.
reading_mnemonic:
This uses the kun'yomi of 石, which you've already learned, and adds a bit of hiragana, so you should be able to read this! If you need help remembering the ころ bit, though, here's a mnemonic for you:

Even a <vocabulary>small stone</vocabulary> or <vocabulary>pebble</vocabulary> could have something amazing at its <reading>core</reading> (ころ). I mean, anything at all could be in that core! Gold, diamonds… Maybe even a chocolate filling! You'd better gather up some small stones and pebbles and start bashing them open to look at their cores. Otherwise, you could be missing out.

examples.en: Fine, I'll have someone else do it!
examples.ja: いいよ、他の人にしてもらうから！

examples.en: Oh, you don't want it? Then I'll give it to someone else.
examples.ja: え、いらないの？じゃあ、他の人にあげるね。

examples.en: Huh, so you deceived someone else!
examples.ja: へー、それで他の人をだましたんだ！

meaning_mnemonic:
Here you have <kanji>other</kanji> and <kanji>person</kanji> joined together by the particle の, which shows that "other" is describing "person". So this means <vocabulary>someone else</vocabulary> or <vocabulary>other people</vocabulary>.

This is more general than 他人, which you already learned. 他の人 can be anyone that's not the speaker, or not the person being talked about. 他人, on the other hand, has an added implication that the person is someone unknown or unrelated.
reading_mnemonic: This uses the kanji's kun'yomi readings, which you've already learned. As long as you remember those, you should be good to go!

examples.en: I wish I had ten million dollars.
examples.ja: 一千万ドルがほしいなぁ。

examples.en: I won ten million yen in the lottery!
examples.ja: ロトで一千万円ゲットしたんだ！

examples.en: Ten million people came to the concert.
examples.ja: コンサートには一千万人の人がきました。

meaning_mnemonic:
You already know that 一千 is "<kanji>one</kanji> <kanji>thousand</kanji>," and that 万 is "<kanji>ten thousand</kanji>." Add all those zeros together (or multiply 1,000 with 10,000) and you end up with <vocabulary>ten million</vocabulary>. 

You learned that 千 is the more common and default way to say 1,000 and 一千 is sometimes used for emphasis or clarity. Well, to say ten million, you almost always say it as 一千万. I mean, who wouldn't want to emphasize ten million! It's ten million, you know?
reading_mnemonic: You already learned how to read both 一千 and 万, so just put those two readings together and you're good to go!

examples.en: Who's this?
examples.ja: この人、だれ？

examples.en: Please look at this page.
examples.ja: このページを見てください。

examples.en: Sorry, my schedule is full on this day.
examples.ja: ごめん、この日はスケジュールがいっぱいなんだ。

meaning_mnemonic:
Remember how これ means "this one"? Well, この simply means <vocabulary>this</vocabulary>. The difference is that これ is used on its own, whereas この goes before a noun. For example, この人 means "this person".

Notice how words like this starting with こ are close to you? We'll be learning a few more of these, and they all follow the same pattern!

examples.en: Isn't that Emily over there?
examples.ja: あれ、エミリーじゃない？

examples.en: That one over there is my house.
examples.ja: あれがオレのうちだよ。

examples.en: That was terrible, to say the least.
examples.ja: いくらなんでもあれはヒドいよ。

meaning_mnemonic:
You need <reading>a le</reading>ns (あれ)? How about <vocabulary>that one over there</vocabulary>? You’re in a camera shop picking out a new lens, and that one over there looks good.

Use あれ to refer to something that's far from both you and the person you're talking to.

examples.en: It says this bread costs $5.
examples.ja: このパン、５ドルだって。

examples.en: Is that U.S. dollars? Or is it Canadian dollars?
examples.ja: それって米ドル？それともカナダドル？

examples.en: The dollar to yen rate finally reached 150 yen to the dollar.
examples.ja: ついにドル円のレートが１ドル＝１５０円になった。

meaning_mnemonic:
ドル is the Japanese version of the English word <vocabulary>dollar</vocabulary>. 

The dollar symbol $ is also common in Japanese, and the pronunciation is still ドル.

examples.en: Which child is Maria?
examples.ja: どの子がマリアちゃん？

examples.en: I wonder which hotel I should stay at.
examples.ja: どのホテルにしようかな。

examples.en: When can you do it?
examples.ja: どのタイミングでできますか？

meaning_mnemonic:
Remember how どれ means "which one"? どの has a very similar meaning: <vocabulary>which</vocabulary>. Whereas どれ is used on its own, どの is used before a noun to ask "which" out of three or more options. So for example, どの本 is "which book (out of that pile)?".

Notice how question words often start with a ど? We'll be seeing more of these!

examples.en: I don't have any money at all.
examples.ja: お金がぜんぜんない。

examples.en: Do you have scissors?
examples.ja: ハサミ、ない？

examples.en: I don't have scissors, but I do have a cutter.
examples.ja: ハサミはないけど、カッターならあるよ。

examples.en: "Moommm, I want apple!" "I can't give you what I don't have, Hana-chan."
examples.ja: 「ママぁー、りんご、ほしい！」「ないものはないのよ、はなちゃん。」

meaning_mnemonic: The <reading>kni</reading>fe (ない) is <vocabulary>not there</vocabulary>. It's not here and it's not there. It’s missing. It's nowhere to be found, so don't bother looking for it!

examples.en: Oh, I don't have my bag!
examples.ja: あ、カバンがない！

examples.en: That's funny. I thought I put them in my bag.
examples.ja: おかしいなぁ。カバンに入れたはずなのに。

examples.en: I opted for a larger bag that can hold a lot of stuff.
examples.ja: いっぱい入るよう、大きめのカバンにしたよ。

meaning_mnemonic:
If there's a <reading>ca</reading>r <reading>ban</reading> (カバン), you'll need a nice <vocabulary>bag</vocabulary> to carry all your stuff in. You can't just throw it all in the car, so get yourself a nice bag instead.

カバン is used for bags that you can close and that have a fairly rigid structure, like satchels or briefcases, but not more flimsy bags that don't close, like plastic or paper shopping bags.

This word can also be written in hiragana and kanji. All versions are pretty common, but you'll probably see it in katakana the most.

examples.en: I can't find a cab at all.
examples.ja: タクシーがぜんぜん見つからないんだよね。

examples.en: Shall we take a cab?
examples.ja: タクシーで行く？

examples.en: Don't use me as a taxi!
examples.ja: タクシー代わりにしないでよ！

meaning_mnemonic: タクシー is the katakana version of the English word <vocabulary>taxi</vocabulary>. The "xi" sound becomes クシー to fit better with Japanese pronunciation.

examples.en: You have worked hard enough!
examples.ja: あなたは十分がんばりました！

examples.en: There is not enough space here.
examples.ja: ここには十分なスペースがありません。

examples.en: Have you thought this through enough?
examples.ja: 十分に考えたんですか？

meaning_mnemonic: You have <kanji>ten</kanji> <kanji>part</kanji>s out of ten. Which means you have quite <vocabulary>enough</vocabulary>. The amount you have is <vocabulary>sufficient</vocabulary> and <vocabulary>plenty</vocabulary>.
reading_mnemonic: This is a jukugo word, which usually means on'yomi readings from the kanji. If you know the readings of your kanji you'll know how to read this as well.

examples.en: I want to go to Western Europe.
examples.ja: 私は西ヨーロッパに行きたいです。

examples.en: Cheese and wine are famous in Western Europe.
examples.ja: 西ヨーロッパではチーズやワインが有名です。

examples.en: I ate so much bread in Western Europe that I gained 5 kilos.
examples.ja: 西ヨーロッパでパンを食べすぎて、５キロも太りました。

examples.en: Wow, Western Europe? That's nice! Which countries did you visit?
examples.ja: へえ〜西ヨーロッパですか。いいですね！どこの国に行ったんですか。

meaning_mnemonic:
The <kanji>west</kanji> bit of ヨーロッパ (Europe) is <vocabulary>Western Europe</vocabulary>. 

Have you ever been to 西ヨーロッパ? You know, places like France, the UK, and Belgium, with all their wine and cheese and beer… Western Europe!
reading_mnemonic: This uses the kun'yomi reading of 西, which you've already learned, so you should be good to go here!
